Correctly serializes nested hash elements when a root element is used with an Entity.Previously, when a root element is used with an Entity, the presenternwraps the array of Entity object in a plain hash, and the Entities endnup serialized as plain strings of the class namen(i.e., {root:[#<EntityFoo...>,#<EntityBar...>])nnThe new code recursively checks for any elements of the hash that respondnto serializable_hash and calls it if present.n

Fix multi-method routes to append '(.:format)' only onceBecause the same path string is used for each loop when the routesnare being built, appending the string using `<<` modifies the original,ncausing multiple '(.:format)' strings to be appended. This fixes thenbehavior, resulting in the proper path output.nnSigned-off-by: Evan Owen <kainosnoema@gmail.com>n

Add possibility for namespace parameters.Specific method options (parameters and description) are now merged with the namespace parameters. So you can do something like below, and the serial parameter will be described for all methods in the namespace:nn```n  desc 'description', :params => { serial => { :desc => Serial of requested object. } }n  segment '/:serial' don  desc Get details on specific objectn  get don  present object, with: API::Entities::Objectn  endnn  desc Reserve an objectn  post '/reserve' don  present object.reserve, with: API::Entities::ObjectReservedn  endn  endn```n

changes: nested namespaces enforce their and parent validations; adds HashStack#gatheradds test for nested namesapces and params/validatorsnnHashStack#gather provides all values for a given keynnWhen Endpoint#run is called it will gather all :validations, not justnthe closest one, and evaluate each one.nnresource :machine don  params donrequires :serial, :existing_machine_serial => true, :desc => The machine's serial number, e.g. 965ACDn  endn  namespace 'serial' don# The custom ExistingMachineSerial validator will be called and enforcednget don  Machine.find(:serial => params[:serial]).firstnendnnamespace 'power' don  # The custom ExistingMachineSerial validator will also be called and enforcedn  get donMachine.find(:serial => params[:serial]).first.power_statusn  endnendn  endnendn

adds 405 response for methods not supported on a resource instead of 404For every resource an 'OPTIONS' route that returns an HTTP 204 response willnbe added. Basic usage:nnclass MyAPI < Grape::APIn  params donrequires :namenoptional :emailn  endn  post :users don# POST /usersn# name=Some+Namenn# This will only have :name and :email keysndeclared(params)n# This will only have name and email keysndeclared(params, stringify: true)n# This will only have a :name paramndeclared(params)n  endnendn

Allow rack/mount cascading to be skipped on headerWhen using header versioning with the :strict policy, Grape currentlynreturns the appropriate error (406 Not Acceptable) but it also returns anX-Cascade header indicating to rack it should keep looking fornother routes.nnWhile this behavior is expected for various applications, some may neednto skip the cascading and explicitly return the error to the requester.nnFor that, a :cascade option was added to the version method. The defaultnvalue is true (keeping backwards compat), meaning that 406 errors shallnbe raised along with X-Cascade headers, just like before. Though, if setnto false, it 406 errors shall be raised with no X-Cascade headers,ntherefore telling the router it should not lookup other routes.n
Minor README edits for cascade.

Extend :cascade to work with all versioning strategiesThe :cascade option allows preventing X-Cascade to be returned onnresponse headers. For Rails users, this is useful because yournAPI exceptions don't get rendered/handled by Rails, but actually sent tonusers. This is particularly useful if you want your user to receive annerror exception in the same format your API supports, and not annunexpected HTML page.nnA more in-depth explanation of :cascade was moved into the code and thenoverview was inserted on the main README on the exceptions section.nnThis commit also changes the order in which versioning strategies arenpresented. The order is now consistent with the order in which thenstrategies were first presented. It also presents the default one,nbefore introducing non-defaults.n
Delete X-Cascade header for default behavior.

Memoize Virtus attribute and fix memory leak.This one fixes a serious problem we faced in production under a heavynload. Investigation led us to the fact that it happens only when paramsnare defined with `type: Array[SomeClass]`. In this case `Virtus`ndynamically create some virtual classes (with `Class.new`) whichninherits from base class with `DescendantsTracker` added which savesndescendant classes into the array. Here we have a leak because garbage collectorndoesn't free these classes because an array still holds a reference tonthem.nnSo at least I can say that `Virtus` isn't designed for creating thingsn*dynamically*. They should be stored somehow statically.n
Merge pull request #1109 from marshall-lee/memoize_virtus_converterMemoize Virtus attribute and fix memory leak.

Refactor and extend coercion and type validationAddresses #1164, #690, #689, #693.nn`Grape::ParameterTypes` is renamed `Grape::Validations::Types`nto reflect that it should probably be bundled with an eventualn`grape-validations` gem. It is expanded to include two newncategories of types, 'special' and 'recognized' (seen'lib/grape/validations/types.rb'). `CoerceValidator` now makesnuse of `Virtus::Attribute::value_coerced?`, simplifying itsninternals.nn`CustomTypeCoercer` is introduced, attempting to standardizensupport for custom types by decoupling coercion and type-checkingnlogic from the `type` class supplied ton`Grape::Dsl::Parameters::requires`. The process for inferringnwhich logic to use for each type and coercion method is encodednin `lib/grape/validations/types/build_coercer.rb`.nn`JSON`, `Array[JSON]` and `Rack::Multipart::UploadedFile (a.k.an`File`) are designated 'special' types, for which specialnimplementations of `Virtus::Attribute` are provided.nnInstances of `Virtus::Attribute` built with `Virtus::Attribute.build`nmay now also be passed as the `type` parameter for `requires`.nnDepends on a monkey patch to `Virtus::Attribute::Collection`, includednin `lib/grape/validations/types/virtus_collection_patch.rb`. See pullnrequest 343 on solnic/virtus for more details.n

Allow inserting middleware at arbitrary points in the middleware stackChanges include:nn* Include the operation when stacking a new middlewaren  The operation gets stored before the rest of the middleware datan  (class, args and block), and we use it later to determine then  order in which the middleware stack will be built.n  Currently support `insert_after` and `insert_before`, plus `use`n  that does the same as before.n* Implement a new `Grape::Middleware::Stack` classn  This class contains the functionality to build the middleware stackn  taking the different operations into account (`use`, `insert_before`n  and `insert_after`). It's mostly based on `ActionDispatch::MiddlewareStack`n  with some simplifications.n* Build middleware stack for endpoint using `Grape::Middleware::Stack`n  Keep the same order for default middleware stack with `use` and use then  new class's `build` method to determine the real order of the finaln  stack.n* Fix small typo in `Grape::Util::StackableValues` (replace `froozen_values`n  by `frozen_values`).n* Update `CHANGELOG` with the PR number.n

[Bugfix] Handle deeply-nested dependent params (#1661)* Repro issue #1659rnrn* [Fix] Handle deeply-nested dependencies with `given`.rnrnBehind the scenes, each call to `requires` or other params DSL methodrnpushes an entry onto a flat list of validators. The nesting structurernthat your parameters can take on is tracked as an up-tree separatelyrnon each scope, but that relationship isn't used to traverse the validations.rnSo, when I moved the dependency checking out of `should_validate?` and intornthe actual validation, the `given` dependency stopped taking effect afterrnyou nested parameters more than one level deep underneath.rnrnTo restore the behavior, I made the validation check recursively upwardsrnto see if it should or should not validate that scope.rnrn* Add changelog entry.rn

Add integration test to show missing documented DSL method (`.insert`)It is documented in the README for this project that there is a DSL method (`.insert`) that can be utilised but this is not the case.nnThe notable passage is:nn```nYou can add your custom middleware with use, that push the middleware onto the stack, and you can also control where the middleware is inserted using insert, insert_before and insert_after.nn```nnThe notable example of this is:nn```nclass CustomOverwriter < Grape::Middleware::Basen  def aftern[200, { 'Content-Type' => 'text/plain' }, [@options[:message]]]n  endnendnnclass API < Grape::APIn  use Overwritern  insert_before Overwriter, CustomOverwriter, message: 'Overwritten again.'n  insert 0, CustomOverwriter, message: 'Overwrites all other middleware.'nn  get '/' don  endnendn```nnThis method is not actually available though and when invoked will raise a NoMethodError. This appears to have just been an error of omission in the original commit adding the middleware stack and extending the DSL to include the ability to interact with it in a more granular fashion (https://github.com/ruby-grape/grape/commit/c2e41f72b344f478abdfdc780461963a994838d3).nnThis commit adds a failing test case which attempts to utilise this documented feature.n

Allow a user to insert a middleware at a specific location in the stack.This commit adds a documented but not implemented feature to allow a user to insert a middleware at a specific point in the stack. It does this by extending the Grape::DSL::Middleware class with a new method `.insert` which delegates down to the already existing methods in existance on the Grape::Middleware::Stack class.n

Support nested dependent parameters`given` will check whether attribute is declared in its scope.nIf not, it raises an error.nn```rubynoptional :angiven a: ->(val) { val == 'a' } don  optional :bn  given b: ->(val) { val == 'b' } donrequires :cn  endnendn```nnIn the example, `optional :a` creates a scope. `given a: ...` createsnanother scope, which parent scope is the one created by `optional :a`,nand attributes `:b` declared in `optional :b` is pushed to parent scope.nnThe bug here is `given b: ...` cannot find `:b` in its scope. Since thenattribute `:b` is pushed to its parent scope. So, fix the code toncheck attribute in its parent scope if it has parent scope.n

delete a reversible stackable values class (#1953)* delete a reversible stackable values classrnrnThe reversible stackable values object was initialized for every endpoint,rnhowever, it is only needed for keeping rescue handlers. The idea isrnsimple, handlers defined closer to an endpoint have higher priority.rnThat test https://github.com/ruby-grape/grape/blob/master/spec/grape/api_spec.rb#L3215-L3232rndemonstrates how it works.rnrnIn our project rescue handlers are defined at the top level, so almost everyrnendpoint keeps the unused object.rnrnThe mentioned behavior is easy to achieve with the stackable values object andrnthe `reverse_each` method. Thus, endpoints keeps less objects andrnhave less code to be maintained.rnrnBesides that, there are a few other simple performance optimizations.rn
